================================================================================
§2. SOVEREIGNTY CONDITIONS (binding)
================================================================================

Any distribution, fork, hosted instance, or derivative of the Software
("Distribution") MUST comply with the following:

§2.1. **No covert telemetry.** A Distribution MUST NOT transmit user data,
usage statistics, or any identifying information to upstream maintainers or
third parties without explicit, opt-in, disableable user configuration.
"Opt-in" means OFF by default.

§2.2. **Local by default.** The core logic of qsim (IPQ, hexagon, quantum
density, Q correlations, cycle, phase integration) MUST function offline.
Integrations with external services (cloud LLMs, remote astro APIs, hosted
inference) MUST be opt-in and clearly marked in user-facing configuration.
External live data sources (e.g. NOAA Kp, Open-Meteo) MUST default to
graceful offline fallback if unavailable, and MUST NOT transmit user data
beyond what is strictly required for the public query (no API keys, no
identifiers).

§2.3. **Right to know.** Any Distribution MUST document its complete
network surface — every endpoint, every direction of data flow, every
piece of user data transmitted. The audit in §3 below is the upstream's
fulfilment of this duty; downstream Distributions MUST update or replace
§3 to reflect their own network surface.

§2.4. **Audit before public commit.** Public commits to the upstream
repository MUST be reviewed for hardcoded personal data (natal data,
identifiers, home paths, API keys, identities, biometric data).

§2.5. **No removing this section.** A Distribution MUST NOT remove or
materially weaken §2 (these sovereignty conditions). It MAY tighten them.
A Distribution that removes §2 MUST also rename the project (it is no
longer "qsim" in the upstream sense) and remove all upstream branding.

§2.6. **Right to fork honestly.** Subject to §2.5, anyone may fork. The
upstream cannot retract granted permissions for past versions.

================================================================================
§3. NETWORK SURFACE AUDIT (upstream, as of 2026-04-25)
================================================================================

This is the complete list of network calls the upstream qsim codebase makes:

| Module          | Endpoint                                                   | Direction       | User data sent           | Opt-in flag                  |
|-----------------|------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------|--------------------------|------------------------------|
| `schumann.py`   | `https://services.swpc.noaa.gov/products/noaa-planetary-k-index.json` | local → public  | none                     | `live=True` (default)        |
| `schumann.py`   | `https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast?latitude=&longitude=...`      | local → public  | optional lat/lon (level 2) | `live=True` AND `location_level>=2` |

Privacy levels for `schumann.get_schumann()`:
- `location_level=0` — no location, only UTC offset; weather skipped
- `location_level=1` — magnetic-zone proxy (default Polska=M); no lat/lon sent
- `location_level=2` — full lat/lon to Open-Meteo (opt-in, requires explicit lat/lon args)

To run fully offline: pass `live=False` to `get_schumann()`.

No API keys are required by upstream. No user identifiers are transmitted.
No telemetry, no analytics, no auto-update checks.

To verify this claim programmatically: `python -m qsim.sovereignty audit`

